
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS formations (
  id BIGSERIAL PRIMARY KEY,
  name TEXT NOT NULL UNIQUE,
  structure TEXT,
  notes TEXT,
  created_at TIMESTAMPTZ DEFAULT NOW()
);

INSERT INTO formations (name, structure, notes) VALUES
  ('1-2-7', '1-2-7', 'https://web.archive.org/web/20190705193350/https://www.football-bible.com/soccer-info/old-football-formations.html


In the earliest days of football there were no specific formations or designated positions. Football was played like a children’s game of kick and run: the ball was kicked long and all the players ran towards it.

In 1863, the [offside rule in football](https://web.archive.org/web/20190705193350/https://www.football-bible.com/soccer-info/offside-rule-in-soccer.html) was formalized with the creation of the English Football Association. The rule stated that any player in front of the kicker is offside and cannot play the ball. The kick and run game was no more and became a game of charge-and-dribble: players dribbled the ball as far as they can towards the opponents goal with several teammates to their sides. Players rarely passed the ball and there was no real formation.  

Because of excess of dribbling and the poor number of goals scored, the FA amended the offside rule. Forward passes were allowed again as long as there were three players between the receiver and the goal line. With the new rule, teams began to play a more organized football which led to the creation of tactical formations.  
  
Below are the most influential formations in the formative years of football.  
  
![The 1-2-7, the earliest football formation, was popular in England in the 1860s-70s](https://web.archive.org/web/20190705193350im_/https://www.football-bible.com/images/image/127-football-formation.jpg)  
  
1-2-7 is the most popular formation in the 1860-70s. With only one center back, two halfbacks, and seven forwards, it reflects the all-attacking nature of football in that era. The strategy at that time was mostly based on long ball to the upfield and charge-dribbling.  
  
The English team played with a 1-2-7 formation when they faced Scotland in 1872. The Scots, represented by Queen’s Park Rangers, utilized a 2-2-6 formation.  
  
Unlike the English, who played a game '),
  ('1-6-3 (Kamikaze)', '1-6-3', 'The 1–6–3 formation was first used by [Japan](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japan_national_football_team "Japan national football team") at the behest of General [Yoshijirō Umezu](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yoshijir%C5%8D_Umezu "Yoshijirō Umezu") in 1936. Famously, Japan defeated the heavily favoured [Swedish](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sweden_national_football_team "Sweden national football team") team 3–2 at the 1936 Olympics with the unorthodox 1–6–3 formation, before going down 0–8 to Italy. The formation was dubbed the "[kamikaze](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kamikaze "Kamikaze")" formation sometime in the 1960s when former [United States national team](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_men%27s_national_soccer_team "United States men''s national soccer team") player [Walter Bahr](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walter_Bahr "Walter Bahr") used it for a limited number of games as coach of the [Philadelphia Spartans](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philadelphia_Spartans "Philadelphia Spartans") to garner greater media and fan attention for the struggling franchise.[[](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Formation_(association_football)#cite_note-12)'),
  ('2-3-2-3 (Metodo)', '2-3-2-3', '[![](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cd/2-3-2-3_formation.svg/170px-2-3-2-3_formation.svg.png)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:2-3-2-3_formation.svg)

The Metodo formation

The metodo was devised by [Vittorio Pozzo](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vittorio_Pozzo "Vittorio Pozzo"), coach of the [Italy national team](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Italy_national_football_team "Italy national football team") in the 1930s.[[4]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Formation_(association_football)#cite_note-4) It was a derivation of the Danubian school. The system was based on the 2–3–5 formation; Pozzo realised that his half-backs would need some more support in order to be superior to the opponents'' midfield, so he pulled two of the forwards to just in front of midfield, creating a 2–3–2–3 formation. This created a stronger defence than previous systems, as well as allowing effective counter-attacks. The Italy national team won back-to-back [World Cups](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FIFA_World_Cup "FIFA World Cup"), in [1934](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1934_FIFA_World_Cup "1934 FIFA World Cup") and [1938](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1938_FIFA_World_Cup "1938 FIFA World Cup"), using this system. It has been argued that [Pep Guardiola](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pep_Guardiola "Pep Guardiola")''s [Barcelona](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FC_Barcelona "FC Barcelona") and [Bayern Munich](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FC_Bayern_Munich "FC Bayern Munich") used a modern version of this formation.[[5]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Formation_(association_football)#cite_note-5) This formation is also similar to the standard in [table football](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Table_football "Table football"), featuring two defenders, five midfielders and three strikers (which cannot be altered as the "players" are mounted on axles). It can be called MM (if the goalkeeper is at the top of the diagram) or WW (if the goalkeeper is at the bottom).'),
  ('2-3-5 (Pyramid)', '2-3-5', '![[R - RSG/main 1/assets/Pasted image 20231211114542.png]]


### Pyramid (2–3–5)

[![](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ab/2-3-5_%28pyramid%29.svg/170px-2-3-5_%28pyramid%29.svg.png)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:2-3-5_(pyramid).svg)

The Pyramid formation

The first long-term successful formation was recorded in 1880.[[1]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Formation_(association_football)#cite_note-:0-1) In _Association Football_, however, published by Caxton in 1960, the following appears in Vol II, page 432: "[Wrexham](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wrexham "Wrexham") ... the first winner of the [Welsh Cup](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Welsh_Cup "Welsh Cup") in 1877 ... for the first time certainly in Wales and probably in Britain, a team played three half-backs and five forwards ..."

The 2–3–5 was originally known as the "Pyramid",[[2]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Formation_(association_football)#cite_note-2) with the numerical formation being referenced retrospectively. By the 1890s, it was the standard formation in England and had spread all over the world. With some variations, it was used by most top-level teams up to the 1930s.

For the first time, a balance between attacking and defending was reached. When defending, halfback-trio were the first facing opposing forwards, when those were surpassed, then fullbacks met forwards as last line of defending.

The centre halfback had a key role in both helping to organise the team''s attack and marking the opponent''s centre forward, supposedly one of their most dangerous players.

This formation was used by the [Uruguay national team](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uruguay_national_football_team "Uruguay national football team") to win the 1924 and 1928 Olympic Games and also the [1930 FIFA World Cup](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1930_FIFA_World_Cup "1930 FIFA World Cup").

It was this formation which gave rise to the convention of shirt numbers increasing from the back and the right.[](ht'),
