  ('3-6-1', '3-6-1', '![[R - RSG/main 1/assets/Pasted image 20231211120027.png]]

This uncommon modern formation focuses on ball possession in the midfield.[[77]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Formation_(association_football)#cite_note-77) In fact, it is very rare to see it as an initial formation, as it is more useful for maintaining a lead or tie score. Its more common variants are 3–4–2–1 or 3–4–3 diamond, which use two wing-backs. The lone forward must be tactically gifted, not only because he focuses on scoring but also on assisting with back passes to his teammates. Once the team is leading the game, there is an even stronger tactical focus on ball control, short passes and running down the clock. On the other hand, when the team is losing, at least one of the playmakers will more frequently play on the edge of the area to add depth to the attack. [Steve Sampson](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steve_Sampson "Steve Sampson") (for the [United States](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_men%27s_national_soccer_team "United States men''s national soccer team") at the [1998 World Cup](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1998_FIFA_World_Cup "1998 FIFA World Cup")) and [Guus Hiddink](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guus_Hiddink "Guus Hiddink") (for [Australia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Australia_men%27s_national_soccer_team "Australia men''s national soccer team") at the [2006 World Cup](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2006_FIFA_World_Cup "2006 FIFA World Cup")) are two of the few coaches who have used this formation. Hiddink used the 3–3–3–1 formation for the Socceroos as well.'),
  ('3–5–2', '3–5–2', '[![](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/af/3-5-2DV.jpg/110px-3-5-2DV.jpg)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:3-5-2DV.jpg)

3–5–2 formation

This formation is similar to 5–3–2, but with some important tweaks: there is usually no [sweeper](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sweeper_(association_football) "Sweeper (association football)") (or _libero_) but rather three classic centre-backs, and the two [wing-backs](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wing-back_(association_football) "Wing-back (association football)") are oriented more towards the attack. Because of this, the most central midfielder tends to remain further back in order to help prevent counter-attacks. It also differs from the classical 3–5–2 of the WW by having a non-staggered midfield. There are several coaches claiming to be the inventors of this formation, like two-time European Cup winning manager and World Cup runner-up [Ernst Happel](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ernst_Happel "Ernst Happel") and the unorthodox and controversial [Nikos Alefantos](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nikos_Alefantos "Nikos Alefantos"), but the first to successfully employ it at the highest level was [Carlos Bilardo](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carlos_Bilardo "Carlos Bilardo"), who led [Argentina](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Argentina_national_football_team "Argentina national football team") to win the [1986 World Cup](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1986_FIFA_World_Cup "1986 FIFA World Cup") using the 3–5–2.[[65]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Formation_(association_football)#cite_note-Wilson-65) The high point of the 3–5–2''s influence was the [1990 World Cup](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1990_FIFA_World_Cup "1990 FIFA World Cup"), with both finalists, Bilardo''s Argentina and [Franz Beckenbauer](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Franz_Beckenbauer "Franz Beckenbauer")''s [West Germany](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/West_Germany_national_football_team "West Germany national football team") employing it.[[65]](http'),
  ('4-1-2-1-2', '4-1-2-1-2', 'http://outsideoftheboot.com/2015/07/07/a-guide-to-the-4-1-2-1-2/


The 4–4–2 diamond (also described as 4–1–2–1–2) staggers the midfield. The width in the team has to come from the full-backs pushing forward. The defensive midfielder is sometimes used as a deep-lying playmaker, but needs to remain disciplined and protect the back four behind him.[[25]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Formation_(association_football)#cite_note-25) The central attacking midfielder is the creative player, responsible for picking up the ball, and distributing the ball wide to its full-backs or providing the two strikers with through balls.[[26]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Formation_(association_football)#cite_note-auto-26) When out of possession, the midfield four must drop and assist the defence, while the two strikers must be free for the counter-attack.[[26]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Formation_(association_football)#cite_note-auto-26) Its most famous example was Carlo Ancelotti''s Milan, which won the [2003 UEFA Champions League Final](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2003_UEFA_Champions_League_Final "2003 UEFA Champions League Final") and made Milan runners-up in [2005](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2005_UEFA_Champions_League_Final "2005 UEFA Champions League Final"). Milan was obliged to adopt this formation so as to field talented central midfielder [Andrea Pirlo](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrea_Pirlo "Andrea Pirlo"), in a period when the position of offensive midfielder was occupied by [Rui Costa](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rui_Costa "Rui Costa") and later [Kaká](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kak%C3%A1 "Kaká").[[27]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Formation_(association_football)#cite_note-27) This tactic was gradually abandoned by Milan after [Andriy Shevchenko](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andriy_Shevchenko "Andriy Shevchenko")''s departure in 2006, progressively adopting a "[Christmas tree](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Formation_(association_football)#4–3–2–1_(the_"C'),
  ('4-1-3-2', '4-1-3-2', 'The 4–1–3–2 is a variation of the 4–1–2–1–2 and features a strong and talented defensive centre midfielder. This allows the remaining three midfielders to play further forward and more aggressively, and also allows them to pass back to their defensive mid when setting up a play or recovering from a counterattack. The 4–1–3–2 gives a strong presence in the forward middle of the pitch and is considered to be an attacking formation. Opposing teams with fast wingers and strong passing abilities can try to overwhelm the 4–1–3–2 with fast attacks on the wings of the pitch before the three offensive midfielders can fall back to help their defensive line. [Valeriy Lobanovskiy](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Valeriy_Lobanovskiy "Valeriy Lobanovskiy") is one of the most famous exponents of the formation, using it with [Dynamo Kyiv](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FC_Dynamo_Kyiv "FC Dynamo Kyiv"), winning three European trophies in the process. Another example of the 4–1–3–2 in use was the England national team at the [1966 World Cup](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1966_FIFA_World_Cup "1966 FIFA World Cup"), managed by [Alf Ramsey](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alf_Ramsey "Alf Ramsey").'),
  ('4-2-1-3', '4-2-1-3', 'https://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2010/aug/04/the-question-is-4-2-1-3-the-future

---

The somewhat unconventional 4–2–1–3 formation was developed by José Mourinho during his time at Inter Milan.[[1]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Formation_(association_football)#cite_note-:0-1) He used it in all the teams he coached, including in the [2010 UEFA Champions League Final](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2010_UEFA_Champions_League_Final "2010 UEFA Champions League Final").[[1]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Formation_(association_football)#cite_note-:0-1) By using captain [Javier Zanetti](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Javier_Zanetti "Javier Zanetti") and [Esteban Cambiasso](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Esteban_Cambiasso "Esteban Cambiasso") in holding midfield positions, he was able to push more players to attack. [Wesley Sneijder](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wesley_Sneijder "Wesley Sneijder") filled the [attacking midfield](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Attacking_midfield "Attacking midfield") role and the front three operated as three strikers, rather than having a striker and one player on each wing. Using this formation, Mourinho won [The Treble](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treble_(association_football) "Treble (association football)") with Inter in only his second season in charge of the club.[[1]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Formation_(association_football)#cite_note-:0-1)

As the system becomes more developed and flexible, small groups can be identified to work together in more efficient ways by giving them more specific and different roles within the same lines, and numbers like 4–2–1–3, 4–1–2–3 and even 4–2–2–2 occur.[[1]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Formation_(association_football)#cite_note-:0-1)

Many of the current systems have three different formations in each third, defending, middle, and attacking. The goal is to outnumber the other team in all parts of the field but to not completely wear out all the players on the team using it before the '),
  ('4-2-2-2', '4-2-2-2', 'Wenger
