The 4–3–2–1, commonly described as the "[Christmas tree](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christmas_tree "Christmas tree")" formation, has another forward brought on for a midfielder to play "in the hole", so leaving two forwards slightly behind the most forward striker.

[Terry Venables](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Terry_Venables "Terry Venables") and [Christian Gross](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christian_Gross "Christian Gross") used this formation during their time in charge of [Tottenham Hotspur](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tottenham_Hotspur_F.C. "Tottenham Hotspur F.C."). Since then, the formation has lost its popularity in England.[[30]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Formation_(association_football)#cite_note-30) It is, however, most known for being the formation Carlo Ancelotti used on-and-off during his time as a coach with Milan to lead his team to win the [2007 UEFA Champions League](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2007_UEFA_Champions_League_Final "2007 UEFA Champions League Final") title.

In this approach, the middle of the three central midfielders act as a playmaker while one of the attacking midfielders plays in a free role. However, it is also common for the three midfielders to be energetic shuttlers, providing for the individual talent of the two [attacking midfielders](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Attacking_midfielder "Attacking midfielder") ahead. The "Christmas tree" formation is considered a relatively narrow formation and depends on full-backs to provide presence in wide areas. The formation is also relatively fluid. During open play, one of the side central midfielders may drift to the flank to add additional presence.



